time.md:7:MCP connection guide examples\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:10:- MCP connection guide examples\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:21:- Bearer `401` challenges on MCP routes include `resource_metadata` pointing to `/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource` so standard clients can discover the mock authorization-server metadata before retrying with a token.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:23:- Legacy SSE aliases open a live `text/event-stream`, emit an `endpoint` event for the matching message POST URL, process JSON-RPC messages through the same MCP runtime as Streamable HTTP, and send JSON-RPC responses back over the stream as `message` events.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:25:- MCP `POST` responses include the server protocol version header. Requests that provide an unsupported `MCP-Protocol-Version` header return HTTP `400` with a JSON-RPC invalid-request error; requests without that header remain accepted for compatibility with simple curl/Postman probes.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:26:- MCP routes are intentionally CORS-open for browser-based tools such as the upstream MCP Inspector UI on `http://localhost:6274`. `POST` responses include `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` and expose MCP/auth/debug headers that browser clients need to read.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:27:- MCP, SSE, REST, OAuth metadata, JWKS, token, and revocation routes answer browser preflight `OPTIONS` requests with HTTP `204`, `Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, DELETE, OPTIONS`, and allow the standard MCP test headers, including `Authorization`, `Content-Type`, `Last-Event-ID`, `MCP-Session-Id`, and `MCP-Protocol-Version`.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:28:- MCP clients should send `Accept: application/json, text/event-stream`; the MVP server is lenient and does not reject missing `Accept` headers because many manual test clients omit them.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:29:- `initialize` returns protocol version `2025-06-18` when requested, otherwise the newest MVP-supported version from `2025-06-18` and `2025-03-26`.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:30:- `initialize` advertises only the `tools` capability with `listChanged: false`; resources, prompts, logging, sampling, durable session, and resumability capabilities are not claimed.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:32:- `notifications/initialized` is accepted as a JSON-RPC notification with HTTP `202` and no response body.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:33:- `tools/list` returns enabled endpoint tools only, with each tool's name, description, and generated endpoint-domain `inputSchema`.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:34:- `tools/list` for valid OAuth Bearer callers returns only enabled endpoint tools included in the token's endpoint permissions.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:35:- `tools/call` on `/mcp` without credentials and `/mcp/none` executes enabled endpoints by name through the shared endpoint matcher. Exact response cases return MCP tool results with text content, and JSON-object responses also return `structuredContent`.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:38:- Configured endpoint or response-case delays apply before MCP tool success, tool-error, or protocol-error responses and are bounded to 30000 ms.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:39:- Response-case tool errors return MCP `tools/call` results with `isError: true`; endpoint-level or response-case protocol errors return JSON-RPC `-32000` errors with `protocol_error` data.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:41:- `GET` on MCP endpoints opens a lightweight SSE compatibility response. `DELETE` on Streamable HTTP MCP endpoints returns deterministic `405 Method Not Allowed` with `Allow: GET, POST, OPTIONS` because durable Streamable HTTP session termination is not implemented.\\ndocs/product-specs/mcp-json-rpc-runtime.md:42:- 